25":"about 1425","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","about 1396":"about 1396","1370":"1370","Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales","of Bangor Fawr,Is Gwyrfai,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Bangor, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Madog","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"Goch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gruffudd Goch ap Madog was born in 1370. He had at least 1 daughter with Gwen ferch Gruffudd."},"et":{"Cir 1370–":"1370–Surnud","1374–Female":"1374–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","Cir 1370":"1370","1425":"1425","About 1425":"umbes 1425","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","about 1396":"umbes 1396","1370":"1370","Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales","of Bangor Fawr,Is Gwyrfai,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Bangor, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Cir 1370–":"1370–Kuollut","1374–Female":"1374–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","Cir 1370":"1370","1425":"1425","About 1425":"noin 1425","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","about 1396":"noin 1396","1370":"1370","Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales","of Bangor Fawr,Is Gwyrfai,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Bangor, Caernarfonshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Cir 1370–":"1370–Décédé","1374–Female":"1374–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1396–Female":"1396–Décédée","1425–Female":"1425–Décédée","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","Cir 1370":"1370","1425":"1425","About 1425":"environ 1425","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","about 1396":"environ 1396","1370":"1370","Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Penrhos, Monmouthshire, Galles","of Bangor Fawr,Is Gwyrfai,Caernarvonshire,Wales":"Bangor, Caernarfonshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Gruffudd Goch ap Madog est né en 1370. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Gwen ferch Gruffud